There's mics in the aisles.

00:00:39.020 --> 00:00:42.450
But I thought we could start
by doing a brief reading

00:00:42.450 --> 00:00:46.539
from the book as is sort of
traditional on these occasions

00:00:46.539 --> 00:00:48.080
because I thought
that would give you

00:00:48.080 --> 00:00:49.490
a sampling of the book.

00:00:49.490 --> 00:00:52.160
And at once give you
a sense of the process

00:00:52.160 --> 00:00:56.530
that poor John endured
throughout the course

00:00:56.530 --> 00:00:58.450
of my writing the
book and the process

00:00:58.450 --> 00:01:02.861
that I endured in
writing about poor John.

00:01:02.861 --> 00:01:04.569
JOHN HORTON CONWAY:
Let me just interrupt

00:01:04.569 --> 00:01:08.610
to say I'm a bit
testy already today.

00:01:08.610 --> 00:01:11.380
So that might very
well-- I'm supposed

00:01:11.380 --> 00:01:14.250
to read these yellow lines
on this piece of paper.

00:01:14.250 --> 00:01:17.010
You don't know which the yellow
lines are, but never mind.

00:01:17.010 --> 00:01:17.510
I do.

00:01:17.510 --> 00:01:19.645
I can see them.

00:01:19.645 --> 00:01:23.410
I'm also a little bit
upset, I must say-- well,

00:01:23.410 --> 00:01:27.340
more than a little bit-- at the
paranoia of Google demanding

00:01:27.340 --> 00:01:34.010
that we produce identification.

00:01:34.010 --> 00:01:38.000
Had I known that I was
to produce identification

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:41.060
before being let in, I would
not have accepted the invitation

00:01:41.060 --> 00:01:42.740
to talk today.

00:01:42.740 --> 00:01:44.285
I'm really serious.

00:01:44.285 --> 00:01:45.410
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: All right.

00:01:45.410 --> 00:01:46.580
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: OK.

00:01:46.580 --> 00:01:48.900
SIOBHAN ROBERTS:
Thank you for that.

00:01:48.900 --> 00:01:54.430
So this is from the chapter on
the Game of Life in the book.

00:01:54.430 --> 00:01:57.590
I thought we'd throw
caution to the wind.

00:01:57.590 --> 00:02:01.730
So I'll just read a bit of an
intro to give you some context.

00:02:01.730 --> 00:02:04.480
"So all hell broke loose
with the Game of Life

00:02:04.480 --> 00:02:06.560
when Martin Gardner, the
'Scientific American'

00:02:06.560 --> 00:02:11.120
columnist, wrote his October
1970 column about life.

00:02:11.120 --> 00:02:11.820
In the column--"

00:02:11.820 --> 00:02:12.620
JOHN HORTON CONWAY:
Capital life.

00:02:12.620 --> 00:02:14.560
SIOBHAN ROBERTS:
Capital life, yes.

00:02:14.560 --> 00:02:17.600
"In the column, Conway
issued a challenge-- $50

00:02:17.600 --> 00:02:19.230
for the first person
to find the piece

00:02:19.230 --> 00:02:22.430
of circuitry in the computer--
the glider gun-- that would

00:02:22.430 --> 00:02:24.950
all but prove life universal.

00:02:24.950 --> 00:02:28.270
And the pandemonium has
continued ever since.

00:02:28.270 --> 00:02:32.510
On a local level, these days
talking about life with Conway

00:02:32.510 --> 00:02:35.420
can cause considerable
perturbation.

00:02:35.420 --> 00:02:39.210
Without much warning, he reaches
his threshold and turns testy.

00:02:39.210 --> 00:02:39.835
It terrifies--"

00:02:39.835 --> 00:02:43.764
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: When he
already is, it gets worse.

00:02:43.764 --> 00:02:45.180
SIOBHAN ROBERTS:
"It terrifies him

00:02:45.180 --> 00:02:47.450
that his worst nightmare
might come true,

00:02:47.450 --> 00:02:51.870
this his life will-- in the
end-- be reduced to life.

00:02:51.870 --> 00:02:55.080
When we met for a session in
the alcove at the Princeton math

00:02:55.080 --> 00:02:58.000
department one day,
he tried to prepare me

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:01.810
for the hellish consequences,
i.e., the wobbly

00:03:01.810 --> 00:03:03.247
that he was about to throw.

00:03:03.247 --> 00:03:05.830
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: I don't know
what a wobbly is, but anyway.

00:03:05.830 --> 00:03:08.960
It says here, "oh god, I
don't know whether to tell you

00:03:08.960 --> 00:03:10.320
now or not."

00:03:10.320 --> 00:03:12.195
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: "Oh
sure, get it over with."

00:03:12.195 --> 00:03:14.444
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: "Well,
it may be upsetting to you.

00:03:14.444 --> 00:03:15.780
It's upsetting to me actually.

00:03:15.780 --> 00:03:17.930
I lay in bed probably
about a week ago,

00:03:17.930 --> 00:03:19.820
in the early hours
of the morning,

00:03:19.820 --> 00:03:22.190
and I've decided, I
have to say, that I'm

00:03:22.190 --> 00:03:26.420
becoming fairly disenchanted
with your biography.

00:03:26.420 --> 00:03:28.780
It's basically because
recently you've

00:03:28.780 --> 00:03:32.460
been asking me these
questions about the Life Game.

00:03:32.460 --> 00:03:33.470
And you know something?

00:03:33.470 --> 00:03:36.190
I hate the Life Game.

00:03:36.190 --> 00:03:39.930
I've really realized I hate
the-- what's that word?--

00:03:39.930 --> 00:03:42.810
damned Life Game.

00:03:42.810 --> 00:03:44.912
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: "Well,
that can go in the book."

00:03:44.912 --> 00:03:46.620
JOHN HORTON CONWAY:
"Yeah, let me finish.

00:03:46.620 --> 00:03:49.090
So I'm scared of the
following thing happened.

00:03:49.090 --> 00:03:51.230
I'm scared of becoming
another one of these,

00:03:51.230 --> 00:03:54.750
John Conway, inventor of the
celebrated Game of Life."

00:03:54.750 --> 00:03:58.330
How many people know about
the celebrated Game of Life?

00:03:58.330 --> 00:03:58.880
I can't see.

00:03:58.880 --> 00:04:00.070
Oh, they all do, don't they?

00:04:00.070 --> 00:04:01.426
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:03.240 --> 00:04:05.890
"As I told you, every
time I turn to a book--

00:04:05.890 --> 00:04:09.450
a new math book-- I look
up a certain sacred name.

00:04:09.450 --> 00:04:13.910
And it says, Conway, Game
of Life, pages 34 to 38.

00:04:13.910 --> 00:04:16.459
And that's roughly all it says.

00:04:16.459 --> 00:04:24.190
And it's quality assassination,
not character assassination.

00:04:24.190 --> 00:04:25.610
I did discover it.

00:04:25.610 --> 00:04:27.820
And it was part
of my little life

00:04:27.820 --> 00:04:30.150
to have discovered it and so on.

00:04:30.150 --> 00:04:33.770
And I don't think it
should be totally excised,

00:04:33.770 --> 00:04:37.010
but it seems to be all
that I'm known for.

00:04:37.010 --> 00:04:40.770
And I wanted you to
somehow set the record

00:04:40.770 --> 00:04:46.510
straight by not doing the
same damn thing again.

00:04:46.510 --> 00:04:48.787
I mean, god, I was quite upset.

00:04:48.787 --> 00:04:50.370
I was so terrified
that I was thinking

00:04:50.370 --> 00:04:53.160
of saying, so to speak,
publish and be damned.

00:04:53.160 --> 00:04:55.465
I don't want anything
more to do with it."

00:04:55.465 --> 00:04:56.756
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: "May I speak?"

00:04:56.756 --> 00:04:58.464
JOHN HORTON CONWAY:
"Permission to speak?

00:04:58.464 --> 00:04:59.520
No, not yet.

00:04:59.520 --> 00:05:00.890
You should appreciate something.

00:05:00.890 --> 00:05:04.140
This was never a big deal
as far as we were concerned.

00:05:04.140 --> 00:05:06.330
We met a bunch of
graduate students

00:05:06.330 --> 00:05:09.010
at Cambridge [INAUDIBLE].

00:05:09.010 --> 00:05:11.180
This was just a recreation,
a game we played.

00:05:11.180 --> 00:05:14.750
Somehow it became a bit more
important later on, or at least

00:05:14.750 --> 00:05:17.080
it did in the eyes
of other people.

00:05:17.080 --> 00:05:18.860
I never thought of
it as very important.

00:05:18.860 --> 00:05:20.700
I still don't, by the way.

00:05:20.700 --> 00:05:23.360
I just thought of
it as a bit of fun.

00:05:23.360 --> 00:05:26.350
In a way, I felt ashamed of it.

00:05:26.350 --> 00:05:29.370
I don't think it counts in
the mathematical community,

00:05:29.370 --> 00:05:32.410
at least in the serious
mathematical community.

00:05:32.410 --> 00:05:34.850
I don't think any of
my Princeton colleagues

00:05:34.850 --> 00:05:36.810
thinks it's of any importance.

00:05:36.810 --> 00:05:37.772
I don't know.

00:05:37.772 --> 00:05:40.310
In a way, it doesn't
count for me.

00:05:40.310 --> 00:05:43.630
So I wasn't going to cooperate
anymore in this character

00:05:43.630 --> 00:05:44.510
assassination.

00:05:44.510 --> 00:05:47.130
I wasn't going to answer
any more of your questions

00:05:47.130 --> 00:05:48.580
about Life.

00:05:48.580 --> 00:05:51.180
Well, I don't mind answering
a few to tell you the truth.

00:05:51.180 --> 00:05:53.370
Just let me say--
how can I say it?

00:05:53.370 --> 00:05:55.670
It was a genuine
part of my life.

00:05:55.670 --> 00:05:59.050
And I told you about my
[INAUDIBLE] time and so on,

00:05:59.050 --> 00:06:02.980
but I really want you to
minimize it rather than

00:06:02.980 --> 00:06:04.000
maximize it.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:04.500
OK.

00:06:04.500 --> 00:06:05.645
Now speak."

00:06:05.645 --> 00:06:06.860
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: "Ha.

00:06:06.860 --> 00:06:08.840
Well, the less said, the better.

00:06:08.840 --> 00:06:12.240
That seemed the best
means of assuagement.

00:06:12.240 --> 00:06:15.200
It's a fool's errand attempting
to reason with John when

00:06:15.200 --> 00:06:17.958
he's in a state."

00:06:17.958 --> 00:06:22.394
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: And I'm
in a state now, by the way.

00:06:22.394 --> 00:06:23.810
SIOBHAN ROBERTS:
So that gives you

00:06:23.810 --> 00:06:26.500
just a sampling from the book.

00:06:26.500 --> 00:06:29.070
But now maybe to sort
of backtrack a bit

00:06:29.070 --> 00:06:33.090
and give you some
broader context--

00:06:33.090 --> 00:06:36.120
this process started
initially when

00:06:36.120 --> 00:06:39.500
I was writing my first
book about Donald Coxeter.

00:06:39.500 --> 00:06:43.730
And everybody told
me I had to talk

00:06:43.730 --> 00:06:46.950
to John Conway about Coxeter.

00:06:46.950 --> 00:06:49.700
Yes.

00:06:49.700 --> 00:06:53.010
And so it took me
awhile to track him down

00:06:53.010 --> 00:06:55.800
because I don't think you were
really using email much then

00:06:55.800 --> 00:06:59.340
and you weren't reliably
answering the phone.

00:06:59.340 --> 00:07:02.880
So I was going about my research
and everything was turning up

00:07:02.880 --> 00:07:05.110
geometry.

00:07:05.110 --> 00:07:07.360
And then finally I
discovered that Conway

00:07:07.360 --> 00:07:09.610
was going to be at math camp.

00:07:09.610 --> 00:07:11.480
I think it was in
Maine that year.

00:07:11.480 --> 00:07:14.500
And so I sought you
out at math camp.

00:07:14.500 --> 00:07:15.990
I don't know if
you remember that.

00:07:15.990 --> 00:07:17.490
JOHN HORTON CONWAY:
I don't remember

00:07:17.490 --> 00:07:18.730
any particular incident.

00:07:18.730 --> 00:07:20.890
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: Right.

00:07:20.890 --> 00:07:23.342
So this is Donald Coxeter.

00:07:23.342 --> 00:07:25.300
My first book was "King
of Infinite Space-- the

00:07:25.300 --> 00:07:27.410
Man who Saved Geometry."

00:07:27.410 --> 00:07:32.710
Coxeter was a very sort of prim
and proper Edwardian gentleman.

00:07:32.710 --> 00:07:34.270
And as I said--

00:07:34.270 --> 00:07:35.530
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Have we
got a picture of him here?

00:07:35.530 --> 00:07:36.070
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: Yeah.

00:07:36.070 --> 00:07:37.320
He was up on the screen there.

00:07:37.320 --> 00:07:40.990
He was known as the
Man who Saved Geometry.

00:07:40.990 --> 00:07:42.506
And then so I
sought Conway out--

00:07:42.506 --> 00:07:44.170
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: He was
one of my heroes, by the way.

00:07:44.170 --> 00:07:44.580
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: Right.

00:07:44.580 --> 00:07:45.320
Yeah.

00:07:45.320 --> 00:07:48.050
And I sought you
out at math camp.

00:07:48.050 --> 00:07:51.755
And in contrast to Coxeter, this
is what I found essentially.

00:07:51.755 --> 00:07:54.210
You blended in so
well with the campers,

00:07:54.210 --> 00:07:56.740
looking exquisitely filthy.

00:07:56.740 --> 00:08:00.360
And you hadn't
slept in a few days.

00:08:00.360 --> 00:08:03.800
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: I should
tell you about math camp a bit.

00:08:03.800 --> 00:08:06.730
Math camp was one
of two math camps.

00:08:09.270 --> 00:08:15.980
It's one for 16-, [? 17-, ?]
18-year-olds good at math,

00:08:15.980 --> 00:08:19.740
nerds, and so on.

00:08:19.740 --> 00:08:25.160
And it wanders around the
United States and Canada.

00:08:25.160 --> 00:08:30.280
And I used to devote one week to
it every year and another week

00:08:30.280 --> 00:08:36.350
to MathPath, which is for
13-, 14-, 15-year-olds--

00:08:36.350 --> 00:08:41.292
or maybe 12-, 13-,
14-year-olds-- fooling around.

00:08:41.292 --> 00:08:42.250
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: Mm-hm.

00:08:42.250 --> 00:08:43.760
And that's what you were
doing when I found you.

00:08:43.760 --> 00:08:44.260
For sure.

00:08:44.260 --> 00:08:45.302
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Yeah.

00:08:45.302 --> 00:08:46.718
SIOBHAN ROBERTS:
But it was great,

00:08:46.718 --> 00:08:48.220
because I got you
in your milieu.

00:08:48.220 --> 00:08:49.025
JOHN HORTON CONWAY:
It's so great

00:08:49.025 --> 00:08:50.600
that I'm not programmed anymore.

00:08:50.600 --> 00:08:54.480
I don't have to read the yellow
lines on this piece of paper.

00:08:54.480 --> 00:08:55.430
Sorry.

00:08:55.430 --> 00:08:56.388
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: Right.

00:08:56.388 --> 00:08:58.890
And so when I was trying to
interview you about Coxeter,

00:08:58.890 --> 00:09:02.670
similarly I had an idea of
what I needed to accomplish.

00:09:02.670 --> 00:09:05.547
But you did tell me how much you
loved Coxeter and admired him

00:09:05.547 --> 00:09:07.630
and how you consider
yourself an honorary student.

00:09:07.630 --> 00:09:10.850
But you also told me
rather a lot about yourself

00:09:10.850 --> 00:09:12.170
at that time and place.

00:09:12.170 --> 00:09:15.140
And so I thought, a-ha,
here is another book,

00:09:15.140 --> 00:09:17.590
because you're such a
fabulous storyteller

00:09:17.590 --> 00:09:19.810
and you do like to
talk about yourself.

00:09:19.810 --> 00:09:22.360
JOHN HORTON CONWAY:
You mean liar?

00:09:22.360 --> 00:09:23.900
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: No, not always.

00:09:23.900 --> 00:09:26.227
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: You
caught me out in one big lie.

00:09:26.227 --> 00:09:27.060
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: Ah.

00:09:27.060 --> 00:09:29.100
Well, I could read that
section from the book.

00:09:29.100 --> 00:09:31.657
Or maybe you should tell
the story about Cromwell.

00:09:31.657 --> 00:09:32.990
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: No, not yet.

00:09:32.990 --> 00:09:33.489
No.

00:09:33.489 --> 00:09:34.830
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: Not yet.

00:09:34.830 --> 00:09:35.800
Save that for later.

00:09:39.180 --> 00:09:43.650
Well, do you want to say a
few things about Coxeter?

00:09:43.650 --> 00:09:44.700
You wrote him a letter.

00:09:44.700 --> 00:09:45.730
This is the letter.

00:09:45.730 --> 00:09:46.896
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Oh, yes.

00:09:46.896 --> 00:09:48.549
I wrote him a
letter when I was--

00:09:48.549 --> 00:09:50.340
I thought it was when
I was in high school,

00:09:50.340 --> 00:09:54.530
but it was apparently when I
was at university-- Cambridge

00:09:54.530 --> 00:09:57.940
University-- possibly
in my first year.

00:09:57.940 --> 00:09:58.970
I don't exactly know.

00:10:02.560 --> 00:10:06.240
Coxeter was a wonderful
man, a geometer,

00:10:06.240 --> 00:10:10.430
living in Toronto, which is
how Siobhan got to know him.

00:10:13.080 --> 00:10:17.690
But he edited Rouse Ball's
"Mathematical Recreations,"

00:10:17.690 --> 00:10:21.355
which I read eagerly at school--
at high school, that is to say,

00:10:21.355 --> 00:10:27.877
in Liverpool-- and then wrote
to him with various things.

00:10:27.877 --> 00:10:29.460
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: A
rather long letter.

00:10:29.460 --> 00:10:30.796
It's a five-page letter.

00:10:30.796 --> 00:10:31.590
JOHN HORTON CONWAY:
Five-page letter.

00:10:31.590 --> 00:10:31.900
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: Yes.

00:10:31.900 --> 00:10:32.840
Rather verbose.

00:10:32.840 --> 00:10:34.830
JOHN HORTON CONWAY:
Illegible to me now.

00:10:34.830 --> 00:10:36.270
But, still.

00:10:36.270 --> 00:10:37.942
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: Mm-hm.

00:10:37.942 --> 00:10:40.150
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Then I
gradually got to know him.

00:10:40.150 --> 00:10:45.100
He's one of a number of
people that I got to know

00:10:45.100 --> 00:10:50.320
and knew in the end
for about 50 years.

00:10:50.320 --> 00:10:54.250
And, you know, then people
who you know for 50 years

00:10:54.250 --> 00:10:58.090
tend to die in their late 90s.

00:10:58.090 --> 00:10:59.753
SIOBHAN ROBERTS:
He was 96, yeah.

00:10:59.753 --> 00:11:00.520
Mm-hm.

00:11:00.520 --> 00:11:02.650
And so I had met
Coxeter when he was 93.

00:11:02.650 --> 00:11:06.440
And I knew him for three years
while I was writing the book.

00:11:06.440 --> 00:11:08.490
And then the book
came out in 2006.

00:11:08.490 --> 00:11:09.402
And then I--

00:11:09.402 --> 00:11:11.610
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: That is
her biography of Coxeter.

00:11:11.610 --> 00:11:12.010
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: Yes.

00:11:12.010 --> 00:11:12.910
Mm-hm.

00:11:12.910 --> 00:11:17.040
And then I went to the Institute
for Advanced Study for a stint

00:11:17.040 --> 00:11:18.620
as a Director's Visitor.

00:11:18.620 --> 00:11:22.490
And I had previously proposed to
John the idea of the biography,

00:11:22.490 --> 00:11:24.550
but you said no, never.

00:11:24.550 --> 00:11:26.890
Why did you say no initially?

00:11:26.890 --> 00:11:32.120
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Well, I was
married to a certain lady who

00:11:32.120 --> 00:11:37.864
I thought would be infuriated by
anything I said about anything.

00:11:37.864 --> 00:11:39.280
SIOBHAN ROBERTS:
Well, by then you

00:11:39.280 --> 00:11:41.060
were divorced from
that certain lady

00:11:41.060 --> 00:11:42.270
and married to another lady.

00:11:42.270 --> 00:11:43.675
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Yes.

00:11:43.675 --> 00:11:45.927
But still--

00:11:45.927 --> 00:11:47.760
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: It all
factors in together.

00:11:47.760 --> 00:11:49.926
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: --it
doesn't stop certain ladies

00:11:49.926 --> 00:11:51.155
from-- never mind.

00:11:51.155 --> 00:11:52.113
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: Right.

00:11:52.113 --> 00:11:54.089
OK.

00:11:54.089 --> 00:11:55.380
But then you changed your mind.

00:11:55.380 --> 00:11:56.820
So when I arrived
at Princeton, I

00:11:56.820 --> 00:11:58.780
called you up just to say hello.

00:11:58.780 --> 00:12:02.370
And you said, hey,
about that biography.

00:12:02.370 --> 00:12:04.170
So how did you change your mind?

00:12:04.170 --> 00:12:07.330
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Well, there
was a rather strange person--

00:12:07.330 --> 00:12:10.860
Matthew [? First-- ?]
at Princeton

00:12:10.860 --> 00:12:14.960
who was some kind of
administrative assistant.

00:12:14.960 --> 00:12:18.200
And I told him some
story-- I forget

00:12:18.200 --> 00:12:22.700
which one it was because I have
a number of stories that just

00:12:22.700 --> 00:12:25.440
get embellished over
the years until they

00:12:25.440 --> 00:12:26.480
become totally false.

00:12:29.100 --> 00:12:31.010
SIOBHAN ROBERTS:
They're all in the book.

00:12:31.010 --> 00:12:32.551
JOHN HORTON CONWAY:
Oh, I don't know.

00:12:32.551 --> 00:12:33.950
Fortunately a few
of them aren't.

00:12:33.950 --> 00:12:40.200
But anyway, and
Matthew said, oh,

00:12:40.200 --> 00:12:42.990
somebody should really
write your life story.

00:12:42.990 --> 00:12:45.490
And I said, well, there's this
young woman who was going to,

00:12:45.490 --> 00:12:47.700
but I said no.

00:12:47.700 --> 00:12:50.850
And he said, well,
why did you say no?

00:12:50.850 --> 00:12:54.590
And I said, well--
well, I told him

00:12:54.590 --> 00:12:58.160
about the certain lady who
would be infuriated by anything

00:12:58.160 --> 00:13:00.560
that was said, so to speak.

00:13:00.560 --> 00:13:03.510
And he said, oh, well, look,
you can talk to your biographer

00:13:03.510 --> 00:13:06.950
and arrange to keep
clear of anything

00:13:06.950 --> 00:13:08.460
that might really upset her.

00:13:08.460 --> 00:13:11.790
Anyway, after some
considerable talk--

00:13:11.790 --> 00:13:14.540
more or less an
afternoon of talk--

00:13:14.540 --> 00:13:17.500
he persuaded me to say yes.

00:13:17.500 --> 00:13:21.450
Now Siobhan was-- this
conversation I remember-- maybe

00:13:21.450 --> 00:13:25.680
falsely-- took place in
January of a certain year.

00:13:25.680 --> 00:13:30.790
And Siobhan was going to
come to Princeton in February

00:13:30.790 --> 00:13:34.890
of that year and was
phoning every now and then

00:13:34.890 --> 00:13:36.930
to make arrangements
or something.

00:13:36.930 --> 00:13:38.140
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: I might
say it was September,

00:13:38.140 --> 00:13:39.640
but, I mean, who's
going to quibble?

00:13:39.640 --> 00:13:40.780
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:40.780 --> 00:13:42.750
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Probably.

00:13:42.750 --> 00:13:49.410
I said, as I remember, so
that means-- it means nothing.

00:13:49.410 --> 00:13:54.440
So when she did
turn up, I-- well, I

00:13:54.440 --> 00:13:58.290
had decided to look
at her face somehow.

00:13:58.290 --> 00:14:03.750
And when I said I
might be prepared

00:14:03.750 --> 00:14:05.420
to say yes or
something, I was going

00:14:05.420 --> 00:14:11.540
to [INAUDIBLE] to seeing
something about her face.

00:14:11.540 --> 00:14:13.700
And I discovered
later I've never

00:14:13.700 --> 00:14:15.580
really looked at her face.

00:14:15.580 --> 00:14:16.180
But anyway--

00:14:16.180 --> 00:14:18.680
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: You were too
distracted defending yourself.

00:14:18.680 --> 00:14:20.013
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Passed over.

00:14:20.013 --> 00:14:22.130
So, yes, I said, in the end.

00:14:22.130 --> 00:14:24.890
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: Right.

00:14:24.890 --> 00:14:28.430
And then something
interesting developed, for me,

00:14:28.430 --> 00:14:32.550
in the process of talking
to you so many times.

00:14:32.550 --> 00:14:36.660
I was at the Institute
on a number of occasions,

00:14:36.660 --> 00:14:41.050
numerous visits over the course
of maybe four or five years.

00:14:41.050 --> 00:14:43.860
And I would go over
to the department

00:14:43.860 --> 00:14:46.970
and interview John on
any number of subjects,

00:14:46.970 --> 00:14:51.162
such as FRACTRAN, which was a
precursor to the Game of Life.

00:14:51.162 --> 00:14:52.120
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: No.

00:14:52.120 --> 00:14:53.790
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: Well, OK,
but just let me continue.

00:14:53.790 --> 00:14:55.040
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: It wasn't.

00:14:55.040 --> 00:14:57.550
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: You
can correct that.

00:14:57.550 --> 00:14:59.630
But interviewing
you so frequently

00:14:59.630 --> 00:15:01.350
and listening to
your stories again

00:15:01.350 --> 00:15:06.630
and your fabulous way of
explaining things in such a way

00:15:06.630 --> 00:15:10.350
that even I could grasp
the gist of things

00:15:10.350 --> 00:15:14.700
or intuit an understanding-- I
realized that it would really

00:15:14.700 --> 00:15:17.520
be a disservice if
I were to approach

00:15:17.520 --> 00:15:21.310
the book in a traditional
way and translate my subject,

00:15:21.310 --> 00:15:23.130
try and set it up
with a third person

00:15:23.130 --> 00:15:23.985
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Did you
say it would or wouldn't?

00:15:23.985 --> 00:15:25.490
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: It
would be a disservice.

00:15:25.490 --> 00:15:25.970
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Disservice.

00:15:25.970 --> 00:15:26.210
OK.

00:15:26.210 --> 00:15:27.380
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: Yeah.

00:15:27.380 --> 00:15:29.230
So instead I just
decided I needed

00:15:29.230 --> 00:15:34.389
to capture Conway and distill
him and let him really

00:15:34.389 --> 00:15:35.430
come through on the page.

00:15:35.430 --> 00:15:38.390
And so what I ended
up doing was allowing

00:15:38.390 --> 00:15:43.110
you to speak in the biography
in extended quotations.

00:15:43.110 --> 00:15:44.620
And I also convinced
my publisher

00:15:44.620 --> 00:15:48.220
to give you your own font,
which was no small task,

00:15:48.220 --> 00:15:51.290
I may say, because it made
the production and layout

00:15:51.290 --> 00:15:53.020
of the book more difficult.

00:15:53.020 --> 00:15:56.110
So John has his own font in
the book, comes in and out.

00:15:56.110 --> 00:15:58.370
We pass the narrative
baton back and forth.

00:15:58.370 --> 00:16:00.920
And I leave it to you
to explain things,

00:16:00.920 --> 00:16:03.410
like the surreal numbers
and the free will theorem

00:16:03.410 --> 00:16:07.730
and all the various
mathy gems and nerdish

00:16:07.730 --> 00:16:10.620
delights that you're
so passionate about.

00:16:10.620 --> 00:16:12.015
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Yeah.

00:16:12.015 --> 00:16:13.694
I don't know what I
can say right now.

00:16:13.694 --> 00:16:15.610
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: Well,
maybe you could tell us

00:16:15.610 --> 00:16:17.985
a bit about the surreal numbers
or the free will theorem.

00:16:21.450 --> 00:16:22.450
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Yes.

00:16:22.450 --> 00:16:23.490
SIOBHAN ROBERTS:
The surreals are

00:16:23.490 --> 00:16:24.800
the thing you're most proud of.

00:16:24.800 --> 00:16:26.680
I mean, the Game of Life,
we can write that off.

00:16:26.680 --> 00:16:28.220
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: I'll
just tell you roughly

00:16:28.220 --> 00:16:29.600
what the surreal numbers are.

00:16:32.320 --> 00:16:33.940
I suppose, more or
less, everyone here

00:16:33.940 --> 00:16:36.400
knows what the real numbers are.

00:16:36.400 --> 00:16:39.470
So that's part of
the surreal numbers.

00:16:39.470 --> 00:16:42.940
The word surreal
wasn't chosen by me.

00:16:42.940 --> 00:16:46.590
It was chosen by
Donald Knuth, who

00:16:46.590 --> 00:16:49.805
wrote a little book called
"The Surreal Numbers"--

00:16:49.805 --> 00:16:51.770
or called "Surreal
Numbers" actually.

00:16:54.670 --> 00:17:00.850
They form an enormous field of
numbers-- absolutely enormous--

00:17:00.850 --> 00:17:04.089
that contains the real
field and lies above it.

00:17:04.089 --> 00:17:05.770
Hence the term surreal.

00:17:05.770 --> 00:17:10.579
But the term surreal also
carries the notion of bizarre

00:17:10.579 --> 00:17:12.150
with it.

00:17:12.150 --> 00:17:14.339
And they are a
little bit bizarre.

00:17:14.339 --> 00:17:17.960
Well, quite a lot bizarre.

00:17:17.960 --> 00:17:22.700
They also include Cantor's
infinite ordinal numbers,

00:17:22.700 --> 00:17:24.530
which are not very
familiar to people.

00:17:24.530 --> 00:17:27.220
So I suppose you know
nothing about them.

00:17:27.220 --> 00:17:30.950
Cantor did a wonderful thing
in the decade-- Georg Cantor,

00:17:30.950 --> 00:17:33.890
famous German mathematician--
did a wonderful thing

00:17:33.890 --> 00:17:37.530
in the decade from 1870 to 1880.

00:17:37.530 --> 00:17:40.580
He founded the theory
of transfinite numbers,

00:17:40.580 --> 00:17:44.030
or just infinite, if you
like-- past the finites.

00:17:44.030 --> 00:17:50.160
Everybody else stopped counting
somewhere at the finite stage.

00:17:50.160 --> 00:17:54.000
Cantor actually copied
the usual way of counting,

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:55.420
starting at one.

00:17:55.420 --> 00:17:58.000
But it's nicer to
count starting at zero.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:17:59.045
So I'll start at zero.

00:17:59.045 --> 00:18:00.970
It doesn't make very
much difference.

00:18:00.970 --> 00:18:05.340
Zero, one, two, dot, dot, dot.

00:18:05.340 --> 00:18:09.170
Everybody stopped,
say, at 2,417,

00:18:09.170 --> 00:18:10.900
or some other finite number.

00:18:10.900 --> 00:18:13.100
Cantor carried on,
imagining counting

00:18:13.100 --> 00:18:16.080
an infinite collection,
getting to the end,

00:18:16.080 --> 00:18:17.870
and then you have
a problem of what

00:18:17.870 --> 00:18:23.890
the next number is after all
the finite whole numbers.

00:18:23.890 --> 00:18:26.770
And Cantor originally
called it infinity,

00:18:26.770 --> 00:18:28.780
but it doesn't behave
like the infinity

00:18:28.780 --> 00:18:32.560
that people know from calculus.

00:18:32.560 --> 00:18:34.190
So after a time he
rubbed a little bit

00:18:34.190 --> 00:18:38.460
of the infinity symbol off and
took the Greek little omega

00:18:38.460 --> 00:18:45.270
as his notion for the first
infinite number counting

00:18:45.270 --> 00:18:47.840
number, omega.

00:18:47.840 --> 00:18:51.080
And then there's omega
plus 1, omega plus 2.

00:18:51.080 --> 00:18:54.300
You see, you can't
afford to go on inventing

00:18:54.300 --> 00:18:56.620
different names all the time.

00:18:56.620 --> 00:18:59.770
You know, there are an awful
lot of finite numbers even.

00:18:59.770 --> 00:19:04.750
And so there's the
number we-- well,

00:19:04.750 --> 00:19:07.200
in England we call
"a hundred and one."

00:19:07.200 --> 00:19:10.580
In America, you call
"a hundred one."

00:19:10.580 --> 00:19:13.120
Really "a hundred and one"
is a little bit nicer, or 100

00:19:13.120 --> 00:19:16.690
plus 1, 100 plus 2, and so on.

00:19:16.690 --> 00:19:19.050
We haven't invented separate
names for all of those.

00:19:19.050 --> 00:19:23.640
Once we got 100, 101
is the next number.

00:19:23.640 --> 00:19:27.470
So with Cantor, omega
plus 1, omega plus 2,

00:19:27.470 --> 00:19:30.480
dot, dot, dot, omega
plus n typically,

00:19:30.480 --> 00:19:34.520
and then omega plus omega,
which is omega times 2.

00:19:34.520 --> 00:19:37.930
Omega times 2 plus 1,
omega [SOUND EFFECT].

00:19:37.930 --> 00:19:43.820
It goes on and on and on
and on and on and on and on.

00:19:43.820 --> 00:19:48.310
They're wonderful things,
Cantor's ordinal numbers.

00:19:48.310 --> 00:19:51.270
It means counting numbers.

00:19:51.270 --> 00:19:55.320
And then I found
some other numbers.

00:19:55.320 --> 00:19:58.360
In fact, I found more numbers
than anybody else-- far

00:19:58.360 --> 00:20:00.860
more numbers than anybody else.

00:20:00.860 --> 00:20:04.060
In particular, there's
an infinitesimal number--

00:20:04.060 --> 00:20:12.010
1 over omega and so on and
omega plus pi and omega minus 1

00:20:12.010 --> 00:20:14.470
and all sorts of other things.

00:20:14.470 --> 00:20:17.530
So it gets a bit surreal.

00:20:17.530 --> 00:20:20.640
It's so horrendously
large, this world

00:20:20.640 --> 00:20:25.460
of numbers, that I went around
in a daydream for about six

00:20:25.460 --> 00:20:29.170
weeks-- permanent daydream.

00:20:29.170 --> 00:20:32.910
I could see these numbers
spread out in front of me,

00:20:32.910 --> 00:20:35.660
or at least I tried to see them.

00:20:35.660 --> 00:20:41.140
And if was a huge world--
really huge-- of numbers.

00:20:41.140 --> 00:20:46.690
And I must admit that I thought,
hm, you discovered it, John.

00:20:46.690 --> 00:20:49.910
Nobody else had ever seen it.

00:20:49.910 --> 00:20:50.902
I'm John, by the way.

00:20:53.860 --> 00:20:58.260
And there's a thing
about [? stat courses ?]

00:20:58.260 --> 00:21:03.969
crossing the American continent
and seeing the Pacific finally.

00:21:03.969 --> 00:21:04.760
He was [INAUDIBLE].

00:21:04.760 --> 00:21:06.400
Of all he surveyed.

00:21:06.400 --> 00:21:08.680
Well, I was [INAUDIBLE]
of all he surveyed too--

00:21:08.680 --> 00:21:11.320
of all I surveyed,
perhaps I should say.

00:21:11.320 --> 00:21:16.280
I wondered whether Cantor
had had similar feelings.

00:21:16.280 --> 00:21:21.080
Cantor eventually-- well, he was
institutionalized several times

00:21:21.080 --> 00:21:25.060
and died in a lunatic asylum
in Halle, which later became

00:21:25.060 --> 00:21:28.992
part of East Germany in 1918.

00:21:28.992 --> 00:21:30.878
A wonderful man.

00:21:30.878 --> 00:21:32.240
Yeah.

00:21:32.240 --> 00:21:34.570
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: And
you said that you're

00:21:34.570 --> 00:21:37.940
disappointed that the surreals
haven't found a broader

00:21:37.940 --> 00:21:40.180
application so far.

00:21:40.180 --> 00:21:41.280
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: I am.

00:21:41.280 --> 00:21:46.320
You see, Cantor's
infinite numbers

00:21:46.320 --> 00:21:49.550
have found applications really
just within mathematics,

00:21:49.550 --> 00:21:51.326
but still applications.

00:21:51.326 --> 00:21:52.700
It's only in
mathematics that you

00:21:52.700 --> 00:21:54.265
want to count infinite sets.

00:21:57.040 --> 00:22:00.440
So I feel that the
surreal numbers

00:22:00.440 --> 00:22:05.405
are so natural that they will
find an application someday.

00:22:08.950 --> 00:22:10.780
The truth is I'm
probably going to be dead

00:22:10.780 --> 00:22:12.810
when they find an application.

00:22:12.810 --> 00:22:14.590
And I don't really like that.

00:22:14.590 --> 00:22:16.820
I was very pleased
to see that you

00:22:16.820 --> 00:22:21.460
quote Peter Sarnak in the book
as saying the surreal numbers

00:22:21.460 --> 00:22:23.000
will be applied someday.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:25.020
It's just a question of when.

00:22:25.020 --> 00:22:26.540
SIOBHAN ROBERTS:
When and how, yeah.

00:22:26.540 --> 00:22:31.950
Now you had an encounter,
shall we say, with Kurt Godel.

00:22:31.950 --> 00:22:34.140
You had read
something that he said

00:22:34.140 --> 00:22:37.450
that gave you hope that they
might crack open the continuum

00:22:37.450 --> 00:22:38.010
hypothesis.

00:22:38.010 --> 00:22:40.340
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Godel
was the famous mathematical

00:22:40.340 --> 00:22:43.610
logician-- in fact, the
mathematical logician

00:22:43.610 --> 00:22:48.380
since Aristotle.

00:22:48.380 --> 00:22:50.530
Possibly one has to go
all the way back there.

00:22:50.530 --> 00:22:53.140
But anyway, he found
a tremendous amount

00:22:53.140 --> 00:22:55.220
about mathematical logic.

00:22:55.220 --> 00:23:00.140
And in 1940 something-- I
always thought it was 1944,

00:23:00.140 --> 00:23:04.590
but I think it's 1947-- he
wrote a paper called "What is

00:23:04.590 --> 00:23:06.952
the Continuum Problem?".

00:23:06.952 --> 00:23:09.920
The continuum
problem was the first

00:23:09.920 --> 00:23:14.310
of the problems--
what were they called?

00:23:14.310 --> 00:23:18.440
The Hilbert problems set
forth at the beginning

00:23:18.440 --> 00:23:21.940
of the 20th century for
mathematicians to work on.

00:23:25.910 --> 00:23:30.860
It was sort of solved
in a sense in that it's

00:23:30.860 --> 00:23:34.150
known that it doesn't follow
from the other axioms of set

00:23:34.150 --> 00:23:37.160
theory and nor
does its negative.

00:23:37.160 --> 00:23:39.950
But that's not really
saying it was solved.

00:23:39.950 --> 00:23:43.240
It was unsolved in a way.

00:23:43.240 --> 00:23:47.762
But Cantor said in this
paper in the 1940s--

00:23:47.762 --> 00:23:48.720
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: Godel.

00:23:48.720 --> 00:23:49.360
Godel said, yeah.

00:23:49.360 --> 00:23:50.443
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Sorry.

00:23:50.443 --> 00:23:52.750
Godel said that
perhaps we would only

00:23:52.750 --> 00:23:55.720
know the solution of
the continuum problem

00:23:55.720 --> 00:23:59.950
when we had the correct
theory of infinitesimals.

00:23:59.950 --> 00:24:04.910
And I thought I had the correct
theory of infinitesimals.

00:24:04.910 --> 00:24:09.763
So when I met Godel-- and
I can't quite remember--

00:24:09.763 --> 00:24:11.040
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: In the '70s.

00:24:11.040 --> 00:24:11.840
Early 1970s, yeah.

00:24:11.840 --> 00:24:12.881
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Yeah.

00:24:15.460 --> 00:24:18.950
Well, I was overawed by meeting
the man, to tell you the truth.

00:24:18.950 --> 00:24:24.770
But I was keen to say I seem
to have the correct theory

00:24:24.770 --> 00:24:26.160
of infinitesimals.

00:24:26.160 --> 00:24:29.810
Now tell me how that affects
the continuum problem.

00:24:29.810 --> 00:24:35.270
And he said, did
I really say that?

00:24:35.270 --> 00:24:36.550
Oh well, I was wrong.

00:24:36.550 --> 00:24:38.026
[LAUGHTER]

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:44.950
Well, it's not kind to laugh
so uproariously because it

00:24:44.950 --> 00:24:46.200
sort of shattered me in a way.

00:24:46.200 --> 00:24:47.116
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: Yeah.

00:24:47.116 --> 00:24:48.410
But I think there's still hope.

00:24:48.410 --> 00:24:51.370
I mean, there's been
people who've tried.

00:24:51.370 --> 00:24:55.820
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: I mean,
yeah, I think he was wrong,

00:24:55.820 --> 00:24:56.840
too, actually.

00:24:56.840 --> 00:25:01.820
I mean, I couldn't see any
effect of it on the thing.

00:25:01.820 --> 00:25:03.370
That's why I really asked him.

00:25:03.370 --> 00:25:06.460
I mean, I couldn't
