00:39:06.620 --> 00:39:09.160
So let me tell you what it is.

00:39:09.160 --> 00:39:14.100
In the free will theorem itself,
in the first version of it,

00:39:14.100 --> 00:39:20.860
we prove that subject--
well, I stated it

00:39:20.860 --> 00:39:23.590
before that if human
experimenters have

00:39:23.590 --> 00:39:25.960
free will-- one
bit of free will,

00:39:25.960 --> 00:39:28.610
they can make one
binary decision-- then

00:39:28.610 --> 00:39:32.210
elementary particles, in
particular spin one particle,

00:39:32.210 --> 00:39:36.030
has the same kind of free will.

00:39:36.030 --> 00:39:40.200
And that just means
independence of past history.

00:39:40.200 --> 00:39:45.380
You can make this decision
independent of past history.

00:39:45.380 --> 00:39:50.850
Well, now-- OK.

00:39:50.850 --> 00:39:56.970
That implies, by an argument I
call the backgammon argument,

00:39:56.970 --> 00:40:02.972
that even-- how can I say it?

00:40:02.972 --> 00:40:08.600
Even if the world is
deterministic but based

00:40:08.600 --> 00:40:13.340
on random numbers,
then still that

00:40:13.340 --> 00:40:14.700
will not simulate the world.

00:40:14.700 --> 00:40:21.820
I mean, straight off it says the
world cannot be deterministic.

00:40:21.820 --> 00:40:26.160
The physical experiments
cannot be deterministic.

00:40:26.160 --> 00:40:28.980
But now people
have always opposed

00:40:28.980 --> 00:40:31.680
to determinism randomness.

00:40:31.680 --> 00:40:34.150
OK?

00:40:34.150 --> 00:40:37.200
But randomness doesn't cut it.

00:40:37.200 --> 00:40:41.614
If you suppose-- I mean,
it's easily-- I'm sorry.

00:40:41.614 --> 00:40:43.280
I'm finding it's
really rather difficult

00:40:43.280 --> 00:40:45.250
to articulate what I'm saying.

00:40:45.250 --> 00:40:51.510
But even if you suppose that
the world operates according

00:40:51.510 --> 00:40:57.280
to deterministic laws, but
that God is playing dice,

00:40:57.280 --> 00:41:01.610
so to speak, and
those dice affect

00:41:01.610 --> 00:41:08.240
what particles are doing, that's
not a sufficient explanation.

00:41:08.240 --> 00:41:14.690
The universe cannot be operated
or simulated by deterministic

00:41:14.690 --> 00:41:19.150
laws plus random numbers
injected into the universe.

00:41:19.150 --> 00:41:20.870
AUDIENCE: Is there
proof of that?

00:41:20.870 --> 00:41:22.420
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Yes, and I
will give you the proof of it.

00:41:22.420 --> 00:41:24.130
And you can follow
the proof of it.

00:41:27.040 --> 00:41:30.650
Here is the way I believe
backgammon tournaments were

00:41:30.650 --> 00:41:33.500
conducted at one time.

00:41:33.500 --> 00:41:35.980
What you need to
know about backgammon

00:41:35.980 --> 00:41:38.140
is comparatively small.

00:41:38.140 --> 00:41:42.210
It is a game played with dice.

00:41:42.210 --> 00:41:45.450
And whether a move is legal
or not depends on what

00:41:45.450 --> 00:41:48.310
the dice [INAUDIBLE].

00:41:48.310 --> 00:41:51.170
And backgammon
tournaments used to be

00:41:51.170 --> 00:41:55.820
conducted in the
following way, I believe.

00:41:55.820 --> 00:42:01.210
Well, you have, say, 50 tables
at which people-- at each table

00:42:01.210 --> 00:42:05.300
two opponents are sitting
ready to move things.

00:42:05.300 --> 00:42:11.700
And the tournament director
says, the first throw is,

00:42:11.700 --> 00:42:14.700
let us say a three and a five.

00:42:14.700 --> 00:42:23.100
And at 50 tables the person who
is first to move at that table

00:42:23.100 --> 00:42:26.370
makes a move-- legal--
for a three and a five.

00:42:26.370 --> 00:42:30.710
And then the tournament
director says, the second throw

00:42:30.710 --> 00:42:32.730
is double six.

00:42:32.730 --> 00:42:35.520
And then at the 50
tables the other player

00:42:35.520 --> 00:42:37.590
makes a move-- legal--
for double six.

00:42:37.590 --> 00:42:40.780
So I hope you understand
the situation.

00:42:40.780 --> 00:42:46.130
Now suppose instead
of doing that,

00:42:46.130 --> 00:42:48.060
instead of throwing
the dice-- sorry,

00:42:48.060 --> 00:42:51.160
perhaps I should
say my model so far

00:42:51.160 --> 00:42:53.880
has been the tournament
director throws the dice

00:42:53.880 --> 00:42:57.910
and says the first throw is a
five and a three or whatever.

00:42:57.910 --> 00:43:01.750
But instead of doing that,
does it make any difference--

00:43:01.750 --> 00:43:04.790
I'm going to say it obviously
doesn't-- if the tournament

00:43:04.790 --> 00:43:08.710
director sits up in his
hotel room the night before

00:43:08.710 --> 00:43:13.700
and throws the dice and records
a five and a three then throws

00:43:13.700 --> 00:43:17.310
them again and records double
six and so on, and then just

00:43:17.310 --> 00:43:20.810
reads them out on the next
day when the tournament takes

00:43:20.810 --> 00:43:21.890
place?

00:43:21.890 --> 00:43:24.500
That doesn't make
any difference.

00:43:24.500 --> 00:43:28.200
I hope people will see that that
doesn't make any difference.

00:43:28.200 --> 00:43:28.700
OK.

00:43:31.700 --> 00:43:34.590
So suppose God sat
up in his hotel room

00:43:34.590 --> 00:43:39.150
the night before the universe
was constructed-- or started--

00:43:39.150 --> 00:43:41.790
and threw the dice.

00:43:41.790 --> 00:43:46.270
All dice throwing can be
treated as past history.

00:43:46.270 --> 00:43:48.320
OK?

00:43:48.320 --> 00:43:49.210
So do you understand?

00:43:49.210 --> 00:43:52.400
I mean, so--

00:43:52.400 --> 00:43:54.800
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] a
deterministic universe

00:43:54.800 --> 00:43:56.660
with random [? oracles ?]
is really still

00:43:56.660 --> 00:43:59.250
just a deterministic universe
because the [? oracles ?] might

00:43:59.250 --> 00:44:00.460
as well have been preloaded.

00:44:00.460 --> 00:44:01.459
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Yes.

00:44:01.459 --> 00:44:04.160
I mean, the random
numbers can be

00:44:04.160 --> 00:44:06.470
thrown before the
universe starts--

00:44:06.470 --> 00:44:10.380
or really independently
of time, I mean.

00:44:10.380 --> 00:44:16.680
And so the proof of the
original free will theorem,

00:44:16.680 --> 00:44:19.470
which says that
the universe can't

00:44:19.470 --> 00:44:28.850
be simulated by
deterministic laws in terms--

00:44:28.850 --> 00:44:33.230
and depending only
on past history now

00:44:33.230 --> 00:44:36.230
says it can't be simulated
by deterministic laws

00:44:36.230 --> 00:44:40.885
depending on past history and
random numbers-- God's dice.

00:44:40.885 --> 00:44:42.510
AUDIENCE: Because
those are effectively

00:44:42.510 --> 00:44:43.202
part of past history.

00:44:43.202 --> 00:44:43.685
They might [INAUDIBLE].

00:44:43.685 --> 00:44:44.360
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Yeah.

00:44:44.360 --> 00:44:46.250
You can treat them as
part of past history

00:44:46.250 --> 00:44:48.630
with-- I hope you see it.

00:44:48.630 --> 00:44:50.715
Nobody else seems to have
made that rather trivial

00:44:50.715 --> 00:44:52.690
observation.

00:44:52.690 --> 00:44:59.920
And you see, so here's this
famous saying of Einstein,

00:44:59.920 --> 00:45:02.695
I cannot believe that God
plays dice with the universe.

00:45:05.181 --> 00:45:07.680
Well, it doesn't matter if God
plays dice with the universe.

00:45:07.680 --> 00:45:08.845
It makes no difference.

00:45:15.670 --> 00:45:23.200
So, yes, the opposite of
deterministic is not random.

00:45:23.200 --> 00:45:23.930
It's free.

00:45:26.810 --> 00:45:29.615
And I don't quite
know what free is,

00:45:29.615 --> 00:45:36.029
but it's not the same
as random because I know

00:45:36.029 --> 00:45:37.320
something about what random is.

00:45:39.940 --> 00:45:41.790
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: Next question.

00:45:41.790 --> 00:45:43.290
AUDIENCE: I'm sure you were
asked a lot of questions

00:45:43.290 --> 00:45:44.914
throughout the whole
biography process.

00:45:44.914 --> 00:45:46.940
So I was wondering which
questions you thought

00:45:46.940 --> 00:45:49.320
were the most effective in
understanding the way that you

00:45:49.320 --> 00:45:51.094
think about the world
and if you could

00:45:51.094 --> 00:45:53.260
give a brief answer to maybe
one of those questions.

00:45:53.260 --> 00:45:55.050
JOHN HORTON CONWAY:
That's to me, is it?

00:45:55.050 --> 00:45:55.925
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: Yes.

00:45:55.925 --> 00:45:58.700
Which of my questions were
most effective in eliciting

00:45:58.700 --> 00:46:02.980
a description of how you
think about the world?

00:46:02.980 --> 00:46:05.680
JOHN HORTON CONWAY:
I don't know.

00:46:05.680 --> 00:46:07.900
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: I tend
to circle around and ask

00:46:07.900 --> 00:46:11.670
a lot of questions
again and again,

00:46:11.670 --> 00:46:15.700
trying to follow my curiosity
and dig around here and there.

00:46:15.700 --> 00:46:20.540
It's a very messy process.

00:46:20.540 --> 00:46:24.510
So I don't know if
I would've put--

00:46:24.510 --> 00:46:26.710
I think, for me, what
really illuminated

00:46:26.710 --> 00:46:31.360
it was letting John
talk and trying

00:46:31.360 --> 00:46:33.400
to capture that
to whatever degree

00:46:33.400 --> 00:46:36.120
I thought would be
understandable to a fairly

00:46:36.120 --> 00:46:37.640
broad audience.

00:46:37.640 --> 00:46:41.240
And you are famous for
being able to explain things

00:46:41.240 --> 00:46:44.530
to any audience really and
grabbing somebody on the street

00:46:44.530 --> 00:46:47.020
and buttonholing
them and telling them

00:46:47.020 --> 00:46:49.380
about the free will theorem
because you want everybody

00:46:49.380 --> 00:46:52.150
to know and understand it.

00:46:52.150 --> 00:46:56.530
So I think it was less
questions-- or not so much

00:46:56.530 --> 00:47:00.400
questions as trying
to paint the picture.

00:47:00.400 --> 00:47:01.390
Show, don't tell.

00:47:01.390 --> 00:47:03.820
So show the man in action.

00:47:03.820 --> 00:47:06.490
And so I think you really
do get a sense of how

00:47:06.490 --> 00:47:10.140
John is in the world in the
book because I'm portraying it.

00:47:10.140 --> 00:47:12.460
I'm not trying to
explain it myself.

00:47:12.460 --> 00:47:13.770
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Yeah.

00:47:13.770 --> 00:47:15.280
While you've been
talking, I've been

00:47:15.280 --> 00:47:17.880
trying to answer the
lady's question myself.

00:47:17.880 --> 00:47:22.140
And I can't do it.

00:47:22.140 --> 00:47:26.860
I really don't know which
has been most effective.

00:47:26.860 --> 00:47:29.180
I suppose the reader of
the book is the person

00:47:29.180 --> 00:47:30.470
to answer that question.

00:47:30.470 --> 00:47:32.400
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: Hm.

00:47:32.400 --> 00:47:36.930
I think most people find that
you speaking in your own font

00:47:36.930 --> 00:47:39.830
does work, which
was a bit of a risk.

00:47:39.830 --> 00:47:42.630
And my editor was calling
it experimental for a while.

00:47:42.630 --> 00:47:44.550
She was quite scared
of the whole thing

00:47:44.550 --> 00:47:45.910
because it's unconventional.

00:47:45.910 --> 00:47:48.380
You're supposed to put
quotes in quotation marks

00:47:48.380 --> 00:47:51.479
and the narrator is supposed
to maintain total control.

00:47:51.479 --> 00:47:53.270
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: A
number of my-- sorry.

00:47:53.270 --> 00:47:53.710
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: No, no.

00:47:53.710 --> 00:47:55.460
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: A
number of my friends

00:47:55.460 --> 00:48:01.070
who have read the book say,
oh, she's caught you exactly.

00:48:01.070 --> 00:48:05.140
So I mean, that's--
well, of course,

00:48:05.140 --> 00:48:08.910
she caught me by just standing
her damn tape recorder

00:48:08.910 --> 00:48:14.780
on the arm of the-- we sat
together in two adjacent chairs

00:48:14.780 --> 00:48:19.000
whose arms had a little flat
surface and she put her damn

00:48:19.000 --> 00:48:23.120
tape recorder in between
and switched it on.

00:48:23.120 --> 00:48:28.310
And so she actually got
my words, all right.

00:48:28.310 --> 00:48:31.110
Of course that meant,
I suppose, that she

00:48:31.110 --> 00:48:35.720
was probing and prodding
in the right places

00:48:35.720 --> 00:48:39.984
to get these words to come out.

00:48:39.984 --> 00:48:42.400
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: But you like
to talk, and I'm a listener.

00:48:42.400 --> 00:48:44.850
So it was the perfect
match made in heaven.

00:48:44.850 --> 00:48:46.180
John talks and talks and talks.

00:48:46.180 --> 00:48:49.352
And you're interesting,
so I was happy to listen

00:48:49.352 --> 00:48:50.185
for hours and hours.

00:48:50.185 --> 00:48:51.830
I have hundreds of
hours of interviews.

00:48:51.830 --> 00:48:52.829
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Yes.

00:48:52.829 --> 00:48:54.876
How many hours, do you
think, all together?

00:48:54.876 --> 00:48:56.542
SIOBHAN ROBERTS:
Easily several hundred.

00:48:56.542 --> 00:48:56.974
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Really?

00:48:56.974 --> 00:48:58.515
SIOBHAN ROBERTS:
Yeah, I would think.

00:48:58.515 --> 00:49:01.001
JOHN HORTON CONWAY:
I was guessing 300.

00:49:01.001 --> 00:49:02.500
SIOBHAN ROBERTS:
Yeah, I don't know.

00:49:02.500 --> 00:49:04.120
JOHN HORTON CONWAY:
Yeah, it seems so long.

00:49:04.120 --> 00:49:05.078
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: Scary.

00:49:05.078 --> 00:49:07.730
I know far too
much about you now.

00:49:07.730 --> 00:49:11.349
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Yeah,
you do know certain things.

00:49:11.349 --> 00:49:12.640
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: Next question.

00:49:12.640 --> 00:49:14.860
AUDIENCE: So when
I was growing up,

00:49:14.860 --> 00:49:18.490
my parents had this
rather colorful book--

00:49:18.490 --> 00:49:22.105
in both meanings of word-- red
cover with a white illustration

00:49:22.105 --> 00:49:22.605
[INAUDIBLE].

00:49:22.605 --> 00:49:24.310
And I read that when
I was growing up.

00:49:24.310 --> 00:49:26.670
I was around 11, didn't
understand most of it,

00:49:26.670 --> 00:49:29.470
but it felt very
interesting in general.

00:49:29.470 --> 00:49:31.316
And when I read it
again a few years later

00:49:31.316 --> 00:49:32.690
when I was an
undergraduate and I

00:49:32.690 --> 00:49:34.650
knew what mathematical
rigor was,

00:49:34.650 --> 00:49:36.900
and I discovered
all sorts of things

00:49:36.900 --> 00:49:39.550
that were even more interesting
that I didn't learn before.

00:49:39.550 --> 00:49:42.160
And when I read it
again a few years later

00:49:42.160 --> 00:49:43.530
when I was a graduate student--

00:49:43.530 --> 00:49:44.580
JOHN HORTON CONWAY:
And what book is this?

00:49:44.580 --> 00:49:44.930
Sorry.

00:49:44.930 --> 00:49:45.471
Say it again.

00:49:45.471 --> 00:49:47.150
AUDIENCE: So this
is "Winning Ways."

00:49:47.150 --> 00:49:48.050
JOHN HORTON CONWAY:
"Winning Ways."

00:49:48.050 --> 00:49:48.839
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:49:48.839 --> 00:49:50.380
And at every level
that I've read it,

00:49:50.380 --> 00:49:51.660
I've read it a few times.

00:49:51.660 --> 00:49:56.230
And every time it's
interesting and every time I

00:49:56.230 --> 00:49:57.235
find out a bit more.

00:49:57.235 --> 00:49:58.610
And the question
is basically, is

00:49:58.610 --> 00:49:59.901
this sort of thing intentional?

00:49:59.901 --> 00:50:03.130
Was it designed to be
accessible at all levels?

00:50:03.130 --> 00:50:05.815
Or did it just sort
of fall out that way?

00:50:09.410 --> 00:50:11.905
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: This is
a book about children's games

00:50:11.905 --> 00:50:13.960
really.

00:50:13.960 --> 00:50:16.840
And so let me proceed
for a little bit

00:50:16.840 --> 00:50:19.620
without attempting to answer
your question because I

00:50:19.620 --> 00:50:22.110
have to describe what
the book is like.

00:50:22.110 --> 00:50:26.100
This is a book that Elwyn
Berlekamp, Richard Guy,

00:50:26.100 --> 00:50:30.860
and I wrote about how to
play children's games.

00:50:30.860 --> 00:50:34.480
Incidentally, I would love to
play Dots and Boxes with any

00:50:34.480 --> 00:50:40.760
of you later on to show you how
good the book is, so to speak.

00:50:40.760 --> 00:50:43.430
It does really give us
information about how

00:50:43.430 --> 00:50:45.470
to play children's games.

00:50:45.470 --> 00:50:47.400
Why children's games?

00:50:47.400 --> 00:50:49.330
Well, because if you
take grown-up games,

00:50:49.330 --> 00:50:52.890
like chess and Go
and so on, there's

00:50:52.890 --> 00:50:57.340
really no hope of
getting a theory out,

00:50:57.340 --> 00:50:58.900
whereas with
children's games you

00:50:58.900 --> 00:51:04.420
can quite often get a rigorous
theory that tells you how

00:51:04.420 --> 00:51:07.730
to win and if you're winning.

00:51:07.730 --> 00:51:15.290
And it's surprisingly
subtle, as I think

00:51:15.290 --> 00:51:17.200
this gentleman made clear.

00:51:20.210 --> 00:51:24.990
I don't know how it--
whether this effect you're

00:51:24.990 --> 00:51:27.810
saying of-- I mean, I'm
pleased to hear your comments.

00:51:27.810 --> 00:51:30.060
Actually, in a way, I'm
displeased as well because--

00:51:30.060 --> 00:51:31.351
[LAUGHTER]

00:51:31.850 --> 00:51:34.010
--we tried to write
it so that you could

00:51:34.010 --> 00:51:35.530
understand it straight away.

00:51:35.530 --> 00:51:39.110
And if indeed it's true that
you have to come back to it

00:51:39.110 --> 00:51:43.975
and come back to it, it's
not exactly a compliment.

00:51:43.975 --> 00:51:45.350
AUDIENCE: When I
was 12, I didn't

00:51:45.350 --> 00:51:48.769
know what a class was or
[INAUDIBLE] theory was.

00:51:48.769 --> 00:51:49.810
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Yeah.

00:51:49.810 --> 00:51:52.490
No, I'm not complaining really.

00:51:52.490 --> 00:51:54.360
I mean, things are
as they are anyway,

00:51:54.360 --> 00:51:56.969
not as we'd like them to be.

00:51:56.969 --> 00:51:59.010
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: But in
a way that sort of nicely

00:51:59.010 --> 00:52:04.250
captures you in that you are--
you're very sophisticated,

00:52:04.250 --> 00:52:07.295
but you're also very
childish all rolled into one.

00:52:07.295 --> 00:52:08.670
JOHN HORTON CONWAY:
I'm childish?

00:52:08.670 --> 00:52:11.850
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: Childish,
juvenile, but yet,

00:52:11.850 --> 00:52:17.020
a very refined intellectual.

00:52:17.020 --> 00:52:18.020
JOHN HORTON CONWAY: Yes.

00:52:18.020 --> 00:52:23.400
Actually I remember
telling Siobhan not

00:52:23.400 --> 00:52:26.010
to romanticize complexity.

00:52:29.780 --> 00:52:32.740
The great discoveries,
at least in my subject,

00:52:32.740 --> 00:52:37.800
are not made by doing
complicated things.

00:52:37.800 --> 00:52:39.700
They are the
discoveries that tell

00:52:39.700 --> 00:52:44.150
you very, very simple things
that people haven't really

00:52:44.150 --> 00:52:45.740
noticed.

00:52:45.740 --> 00:52:52.990
Actually the case I just
mentioned before of randomness

00:52:52.990 --> 00:52:56.080
not cutting it, so to speak,
in the free will theorem

00:52:56.080 --> 00:52:58.490
is an instance of this.

00:52:58.490 --> 00:53:02.300
Look, that's a very, very
simple observation, OK?

00:53:02.300 --> 00:53:05.180
Einstein didn't make it.

00:53:05.180 --> 00:53:06.610
Isn't that fantastic?

00:53:06.610 --> 00:53:11.860
I feel so proud that we
made this observation which

00:53:11.860 --> 00:53:15.780
I can explain to this
audience quite easily.

00:53:15.780 --> 00:53:19.070
Einstein didn't get it.

00:53:19.070 --> 00:53:21.860
It's absolutely fantastic.

00:53:21.860 --> 00:53:24.230
Einstein made lots of
simple observations.

00:53:24.230 --> 00:53:28.200
Einstein's observations were
not-- he wasn't terribly good

00:53:28.200 --> 00:53:31.420
at mathematics, as he says
himself in certain places.

00:53:31.420 --> 00:53:36.120
He didn't know certain
abstract theories.

00:53:36.120 --> 00:53:40.520
But he thought in a
very, very simple way.

00:53:40.520 --> 00:53:42.644
This is just one of
the simple things

00:53:42.644 --> 00:53:43.810
that Einstein didn't notice.

00:53:43.810 --> 00:53:45.300
Actually it may be the only one.

00:53:45.300 --> 00:53:47.880
I don't know.

00:53:47.880 --> 00:53:54.565
So, I mean, it's hard to
make new simple discoveries.

00:53:54.565 --> 00:53:57.760
It really is.

00:53:57.760 --> 00:54:01.170
When you make them, of course,
everybody understands them.

00:54:01.170 --> 00:54:03.229
I hope.

00:54:03.229 --> 00:54:05.770
SIOBHAN ROBERTS: So maybe we'll
