00:54:05.770 --> 00:54:07.024
And then--

00:54:07.024 --> 00:54:07.880
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:54:07.880 --> 00:54:10.126
My question is more
on building on that

00:54:10.126 --> 00:54:14.760
thought that there are some
discoveries that you keep

00:54:14.760 --> 00:54:17.210
figuring out as you
go through your day

00:54:17.210 --> 00:54:19.380
while playing some
game, say tic-tac-toe.

00:54:19.380 --> 00:54:21.560
And the first time I'd
realized when I was a kid,

00:54:21.560 --> 00:54:24.800
oh, this can be
won all the time.

00:54:24.800 --> 00:54:28.380
That's the basic that
a child first learns.

00:54:28.380 --> 00:54:32.260
And then some games you can
count plus 11 each time, plus 1

00:54:32.260 --> 00:54:32.760
to 10.

00:54:32.760 --> 00:54:34.385
Then you realize if
you start with one,

00:54:34.385 --> 00:54:35.560
that you'll always win.

00:54:35.560 --> 00:54:38.960
And there are certain
games, but they actually

00:54:38.960 --> 00:54:41.750
[INAUDIBLE] game [INAUDIBLE].

00:54:41.750 --> 00:54:44.780
But they don't really
cut into applications

00:54:44.780 --> 00:54:46.840
that you also mentioned
that hopefully you're

00:54:46.840 --> 00:54:49.980
seeing hopefully
before-- in your lifetime

00:54:49.980 --> 00:54:52.770
you would like to see some
application of the theory.

00:54:52.770 --> 00:54:54.990
So what are the
theories you think

00:54:54.990 --> 00:54:59.100
will actually be most
profound in a decade or two?

00:54:59.100 --> 00:55:02.690
And then you'll be
really proud of those.

00:55:02.690 --> 00:55:04.250
JOHN HORTON CONWAY:
It's hard to say.

00:55:04.250 --> 00:55:07.350
I mean, I'd like to
get back, in a way,

00:55:07.350 --> 00:55:10.330
to the surreal numbers, because
the surreal numbers were

00:55:10.330 --> 00:55:14.160
an application of playing games.

00:55:14.160 --> 00:55:17.310
At one time the
British Go champion

00:55:17.310 --> 00:55:21.000
was a member of the Cambridge
University mathematics

00:55:21.000 --> 00:55:23.320
department.

00:55:23.320 --> 00:55:25.440
Many of you will
know the game of Go.

00:55:25.440 --> 00:55:27.370
Many of you will not probably.

00:55:27.370 --> 00:55:31.760
But I tried to
understand-- he brought

00:55:31.760 --> 00:55:35.410
in various friends of his
and they played Go games.

00:55:35.410 --> 00:55:37.490
And in Cambridge
people would stand

00:55:37.490 --> 00:55:40.730
around kibitzing or
asking each other what

00:55:40.730 --> 00:55:42.960
this move-- why this move
was better than that move

00:55:42.960 --> 00:55:45.380
and so on.

00:55:45.380 --> 00:55:50.080
I tried to understand these
comments and never did.

00:55:50.080 --> 00:55:54.260
Let me say I never understood
much about Go anyway.

00:55:54.260 --> 00:55:59.580
But I did notice that
near the end of the game,

00:55:59.580 --> 00:56:04.960
Go broke up into a
sum of smaller games.

00:56:04.960 --> 00:56:09.310
And I had been
meaning to analyze

00:56:09.310 --> 00:56:15.300
the notion of sum of smaller
games for quite some time.

00:56:15.300 --> 00:56:19.110
And that prompted me
to actually do it.

00:56:19.110 --> 00:56:22.760
And then I discovered,
in particular,

00:56:22.760 --> 00:56:25.810
that some games
behaved like numbers.

00:56:25.810 --> 00:56:28.600
I now say [? were ?] numbers.

00:56:28.600 --> 00:56:34.810
And notice that you've
got a simpler development

00:56:34.810 --> 00:56:41.030
of the theory of real numbers
by just regarding them as games.

00:56:41.030 --> 00:56:44.050
There's an application
of childish game

00:56:44.050 --> 00:56:45.890
theory to numbers.

00:56:49.840 --> 00:56:51.905
But it didn't stop
at the real numbers.

00:56:51.905 --> 00:56:55.830
It went on to the
surreal numbers.

00:56:55.830 --> 00:57:05.770
And that's a lovely thing
for me because I like-- well,

00:57:05.770 --> 00:57:08.660
in England we say taking the
[? mickey ?] out of people.

00:57:08.660 --> 00:57:11.800
I mean, it means-- I suppose
it means taking the microphone,

00:57:11.800 --> 00:57:13.600
but I'm not sure.

00:57:13.600 --> 00:57:17.110
It means making fun of
people who are particularly

00:57:17.110 --> 00:57:19.960
pompous or something.

00:57:19.960 --> 00:57:28.220
And here is this serious
theory of the foundations

00:57:28.220 --> 00:57:30.340
of the real numbers
and everything

00:57:30.340 --> 00:57:34.560
which was developed in the 19th
century by people with beards.

00:57:34.560 --> 00:57:42.120
And it came out-- I mean,
this is a simpler theory

00:57:42.120 --> 00:57:44.700
than that that came
out of studying

00:57:44.700 --> 00:57:50.020
childish games in a way
that people hadn't thought

00:57:50.020 --> 00:57:52.730
was worthwhile before.

00:57:52.730 --> 00:57:54.110
So there's an application.

00:57:54.110 --> 00:57:57.730
It's not quite what
you're talking about.

00:57:57.730 --> 00:58:00.395
In fact, it's an application--
you were talking about sort

00:58:00.395 --> 00:58:02.940
of [INAUDIBLE] [? implies ?]
[? C, ?] B applied to C.

00:58:02.940 --> 00:58:08.830
This is A applied to
B. But it's amazing.

00:58:08.830 --> 00:58:14.910
I find mathematics-- I've
always found mathematics

00:58:14.910 --> 00:58:17.540
really astonishing
because I don't

00:58:17.540 --> 00:58:19.490
know where it all comes from.

00:58:19.490 --> 00:58:26.150
I don't know what the ontology
of mathematical ideas is.

00:58:26.150 --> 00:58:32.990
Where is two or three or omega?

00:58:32.990 --> 00:58:39.370
Wherever they are, it's a place
that has a certain stability.

00:58:39.370 --> 00:58:43.630
I like to compare
numbers to cats.

00:58:43.630 --> 00:58:47.580
Well, you see, there's
no doubt that cats exist.

00:58:47.580 --> 00:58:51.690
And part of the reason
I'm sure about that

00:58:51.690 --> 00:58:56.530
is that when you push
a cat, it pushes back.

00:58:56.530 --> 00:59:00.570
It doesn't want to go in
the direction you push it.

00:59:00.570 --> 00:59:04.300
It wants to do its own thing.

00:59:04.300 --> 00:59:06.980
The same is true of numbers.

00:59:06.980 --> 00:59:10.200
I mean, you can't make
numbers do what they don't

00:59:10.200 --> 00:59:12.567
want to do in a certain sense.

00:59:12.567 --> 00:59:15.150
Of course, numbers are different
to cats in some other senses.

00:59:15.150 --> 00:59:16.272
I realize that.

00:59:16.272 --> 00:59:16.990
[LAUGHTER]

00:59:19.190 --> 00:59:22.770
When you're a
little toddler, you

00:59:22.770 --> 00:59:27.470
scream to your
mother about things.

00:59:27.470 --> 00:59:28.530
I don't know.

00:59:28.530 --> 00:59:31.670
And your mother responds.

00:59:31.670 --> 00:59:35.470
Your father might
respond too, but anyway.

00:59:35.470 --> 00:59:38.740
You don't scream at the wall.

00:59:38.740 --> 00:59:42.300
The wall interferes with
your natural progression.

00:59:42.300 --> 00:59:46.347
You just can't walk through
walls, but you don't try.

00:59:46.347 --> 00:59:48.930
And you don't scream at the wall
in order [INAUDIBLE] let you.

00:59:52.280 --> 00:59:56.400
What I'm trying to
say is obstinacy

00:59:56.400 --> 01:00:01.205
of things is some kind of
mark of real existence.

01:00:06.860 --> 01:00:07.360
OK.

01:00:11.550 --> 01:00:15.000
Well, I don't know.

01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:17.920
I've been worried
about the sense

01:00:17.920 --> 01:00:23.390
in which mathematical notions
exist for a very long time--

01:00:23.390 --> 01:00:27.470
ever since I was about 10
probably-- but with gradually

01:00:27.470 --> 01:00:30.416
increasing knowledge
and [? abilities ?]

01:00:30.416 --> 01:00:34.730
and so on of the way in
which things [INAUDIBLE].

01:00:34.730 --> 01:00:35.940
How do they exist?

01:00:35.940 --> 01:00:37.390
I mean, they seem to.

01:00:37.390 --> 01:00:38.710
And the existence--

01:00:38.710 --> 01:00:42.600
People are very confused.

01:00:42.600 --> 01:00:47.022
They think that things
like two are concepts.

01:00:47.022 --> 01:00:48.310
They aren't.

01:00:48.310 --> 01:00:52.150
A concept means something
we conceive in our heads.

01:00:52.150 --> 01:00:56.310
Well, two was there a long time
before there were any people

01:00:56.310 --> 01:00:58.790
to conceive things.

01:00:58.790 --> 01:01:01.250
The statement that Mars has
two satellites-- they're

01:01:01.250 --> 01:01:05.060
called Phobos and
Deimos now-- was true

01:01:05.060 --> 01:01:08.980
long before there were
any humans to conceive.

01:01:08.980 --> 01:01:14.050
So abstract things are
not the same as concepts.

01:01:14.050 --> 01:01:19.170
A unicorn isn't the same as
the concept of a unicorn.

01:01:19.170 --> 01:01:21.800
The concept of a unicorn exists.

01:01:21.800 --> 01:01:24.020
Unicorns don't.

01:01:24.020 --> 01:01:26.080
The concept of a horse exists.

01:01:26.080 --> 01:01:27.180
Horses do too.

01:01:30.680 --> 01:01:31.970
Well, I don't understand it.

01:01:31.970 --> 01:01:34.760
I've been thinking about
it for a long, long time

01:01:34.760 --> 01:01:37.920
and at different
degrees of depth.

01:01:37.920 --> 01:01:42.240
You see, when things
get a little bit more

01:01:42.240 --> 01:01:48.540
abstract or a little bit
more infinite or something,

01:01:48.540 --> 01:01:52.100
the problems are still the same.

01:01:52.100 --> 01:02:00.690
Omega, this infinite number
I spoke of, it exists.

01:02:00.690 --> 01:02:07.170
It's not so easy to see
how its existence differs

01:02:07.170 --> 01:02:11.710
from the existence of two, but--

01:02:11.710 --> 01:02:13.019
My.

01:02:13.019 --> 01:02:13.560
I don't know.

01:02:13.560 --> 01:02:14.060
I'm sorry.

01:02:14.060 --> 01:02:17.160
I'm just going to lapse
into incomprehensibility.

01:02:17.160 --> 01:02:19.152
I'd better just stop.

